HOW TO
USE THE
OXYGEN MASK
Jet aircraft fly at high altitude and the cabin is pressurized tor your
comfort. If cabin pressure ever was lost, you would be breathing high
altitude "thin" air... so it is imperative that cigars and cigarettes be
extinguished immediately and oxygen masks be put on as shown below.
1. WHERE TO LOCATE MASKS.
Oxygen masks are in a seat back
compartment or overhead compartment
if no seat in front of you. If oxygen is
ever required, compartment doors
open automatically. For children's use,
a spare mask is available at each row.
2. HOW TO USE MASKS.
Remain
seated. Grasp nearest mask and
pull it from its holder. A cord turns
oxygen on as you pull mask to you.
Remove the plastic bag, coiled oxygen
tube and head band stored inside the
mask. Promptly place mask over nose
and mouth.
The oxygen supply tube is
long enough that you may relax
comfortably in your seat after mask
is on your face.
HOW TO ADJUST MASKS
3. PLACE MASK OVER NOSE AND
MOUTH. Slip head band over head and
adjust length for comfortable fit. Do
not overtighten head band as this may
misshape mask and cause discomfort.

PROTECTIVE POSITION
Sit well back in seatâ€”
pull seat belt tight-
assume position in illustration-
keep position until plane stops.
Back cushion is floatable-
grasp it at bottom-
pull to detach from frame.
FEDERAL AVIATION REGULATIONS REQUIRE:
DURING TAKE OFF AND LANDING YOUR SEAT BACK AND TRAY TABLE MUST BE
IN THE UPRIGHT POSITION AND YOUR CARRY-ON LUGGAGE PLACED UNDER A SEAT.
